    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(Heb.: 18:14-16) Amidst thunder, Jahve hurled lightnings as arrows upon David's enemies, and the breath of His anger laid bare the beds of the flood to the very centre of the earth, in order to rescue the sunken one. Thunder is the rumble of God, and as it were the hollow murmur of His mouth, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Job 37:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". עליון, the Most High, is the name of God as the inapproachable Judge, who governs all things. The third line of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 18:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is erroneously repeated from the preceding strophe. It cannot be supported on grammatical grounds by ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 9:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", since קול נתן, edere vocem, has a different meaning from the נתן קלת, dare tonitrua, of that passage. The symmetry of the strophe structure is also against it; and it is wanting both in 2 Sam. nd in the lxx. רב, which, as the opposite of מעט ",
