        "class": "",
        "text": " : רב in pause  equals  רב (the ō passing over into the broader  like עז instead of עז in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 49:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ")  equals  רבב, cognate with רבה, רמה; but the forms סב, סבּוּ, here, and in every other instance, have but a very questionable existence, as e.g., רב, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 54:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", is more probably an adjective than the third person praet. (cf. Bttcher, Neue Aehrenlese No. 635, 1066). The suffixes ēm do not refer to the arrows, i.e., lightnings, but to David's foes. המם means both to put in commotion and to destroy by confounding, ",
